##48 hours of volunteer service at Little Tangshan, Huanggang

Wechat, boyangcongpeople

The function introduces, peels off the human shell, records the real sensible life. Presented by the in-depth Reporting Department of the Beijing News.

At 10:30 p.m. on January 28, the first patients were admitted to the Dabie Mountains Regional Medical Center. Ye Bao at home to see patients live in the video, crying, "finally can safely eat a meal. "

Dabie Mountains Regional Medical Centre. Photo provided by respondents

By Han Qinke, Beijing News

Editor | Jing Yi Wang, proofread | Zhuo Wei

The text is about 2623 words long and takes about five minutes to read

In the early hours of January 26, Ye Bao, a "post-90s" volunteer from Huanggang, posted a group Qr Code on her friend's circle to help recruit volunteers for the renovation project of the new hospital district in Central Huanggang. "Do not know how many people can call" , with apprehension, she fell asleep.

Huanggang, with a population of less than 8m just over an hour's drive from the centre of Wuhan, is one of the regions hardest hit by the new pneumonia. As of 2400 hours on January 30,2020, Huanggang has reported a total of 573 cases of COVID-19 pneumonia, 12 deaths, six cured cases, and the number of confirmed cases and deaths is second only to Wuhan.

In order to treat and isolate patients more effectively, on January 25, the Municipal Party Committee and government of Huanggang, Hubei Province decided to use the Dabie Mountains Regional Medical Center as a centralized Treatment Center for fever patients, requiring it to be transformed into the "Xiaotangshan" of Huanggang within two days, 1,000 beds.

It was supposed to be opened in four months as the new wing of Huanggang's Central Hospital, the main body of which has been completed, as well as indoor and outdoor decoration. Now, departments, hospitals and volunteers have 48 hours to finish the renovation, hardening and brightening, cleaning floors, setting up wards and so on.

The volunteers gathered quickly

A light rain turns to sleet in Huanggang on January 26, with temperatures ranging from 5 °C to 3 °C.

By the time Ye woke up at 8 a.m. , the volunteer group had grown to more than 200 members. By 9:00 am, more than 20 fast-moving volunteers had gathered at the gate of the Dabie Mountains Regional Medical Centre in Huanggang's version of Florida.

The volunteers were responsible for the handling of medical equipment in a 3-7-storey quarantine zone at the Dabie Mountains Regional Medical Centre, the initial arrangement of wards and floor cleaning in 1-3 buildings.

"The quilts were so heavy that it was difficult for the girls to move them, so they had to be dragged all the way to the building from the car. " Ye Bao saw a dozen or so quilts piled up outside the elevator doors, more than half a person high, and three women of modest stature gasping for breath, work together to lift the package into the elevator.

Volunteers drag a half-man-tall package to a designated spot. Photo courtesy of the respondents

At 11:00 p.m. , Ye Bao posted on her friends' circle, "we need someone to drop off the goods at our new hospital. ". Soon, more volunteers joined in, and in the afternoon, more than 100 volunteers showed up.

Due to the severity of the outbreak and the remoteness of the Dabie Mountains Regional Medical Centre, the hospital was unable to find enough workers in the short term and had to rely partly on volunteers. "We hire people at 600 yuan a day, " a hospital worker told the Beijing News. "Many people don't want to come, but the volunteers work in the hospital from morning to night and don't want anything. "

Yeung Kwong (not his real name) , a 49-year-old bus driver, was among the volunteers. He was part of three groups of 209 people -- Six wechat groups, each with 200 to 400 people. On January 26, Yeung Kwong had lunch and drove a dozen miles to the Dabie Mountains Regional Medical Center to do what he could to combat the outbreak.

With the increase in the number of volunteers, Ye Bao automatically became a "command announcer. ". Cheng Min (not her real name) , who is in charge of procurement at Huanggang's Central Hospital, told her when the trucks would arrive, how many people would be needed to move them and where the supplies would need to be placed. She then forwarded the information to the volunteers. Hospital staff do the inventory, and volunteers unload and carry the goods to designated locations.

Work continued until 2 am the next day, we finally arrived at the hospital, the last car bed moved out. The newly renovated Dabie Mountains Medical Center has little furniture, and hospital staff and volunteers are squatting on the floor.

That day, 57-year-old Cheng Min walked more than 60,000 steps, Ye Bao was shouted hoarse voice.

At 11:30 pm on January 26, Ye Bao posted the task for the next day: installing 1,000 beds, 2,000 garbage cans and all the hygiene in the hospital. She did not forget to remind everyone to pay attention to their physical condition, wear a mask.

"like these things don't cost anything. "

On January 27, Huanggang turned overcast and cloudy with temperatures ranging from 5 °C to 0 °C.

"I've never seen so many garbage cans, " Ye Bao sighed. In her video, installed trash cans fill half the lobby. "There has to be a trash can next to every bed. "

While the ladies were installing trash cans indoors, the men were moving beds around. Each bed takes 10 people to get off the truck and six to get into the ward. At temperatures approaching 0 °C, volunteers carrying hospital beds change their masks in less than two hours, soaking them in sweat and fumes.

To improve work efficiency, hospital staff put all volunteers in groups of 10 into more than 30 groups, each group has a contact person, Ye Bao is responsible for assisting Cheng Min to communicate the task to the contact person.

At 11:00 noon, 1,000 beds were delivered with matching cabinets. A dozen teams lined up to connect a conveyor belt between the truck and the elevator, small cabinets moving quickly in the hands of volunteers. "We need 100 on each floor. " According to the hospital staff, within two hours, all the cabinets have been placed in the designated area.

Cheng said that the workload of a hospital bed includes the installation of the bed, bedding, bedside cabinets and garbage bins, and the cleaning of the area around the bed, which takes several hours for one person to complete, "The volunteers worked 1,000 beds in a single day. It was hard work. "

It had just rained and the ground was muddy. Volunteers lifted the hospital bed and carried it into the building. Photo courtesy of the respondents

"Do you have a couple of cokes from a caring person? " Ye Bao posted in her circle of friends. An hour later, a resident wearing a three-layer mask drove up with dozens of bottles of coke of various sizes. This made ye Bao feel once again the unity of the people of Huanggang.

On the second day of the renovation of the Dabie Mountains Regional Medical Center, the corner of the hospital lobby was filled with boxes of mineral water, instant noodles and snacks.

"I said in my friends' circle that we needed toilet brushes and steel-wool balls, and in a short time, hundreds of them were sent to the door of the hospital. I don't know who sent them, " Ye said, "Some of the commissaries have just sent in their own stock as if it were free. "

Comes in handy, along with the cleaning supplies and the tech guys. Soon after ye Bao and a friend's circle posted a video asking for help from a plumber, several technicians arrived with tools.

"finally, a meal in peace. "

On January 28, Huanggang turned overcast and cloudy with temperatures ranging from 5 °C to 0 °C.

At 8:30 a.m. , several volunteers with infrared thermometers took the temperature of everyone present.

"Do not come home Wuhan, home fever do not come, do not come unwell" , this is ye Bao in the call for volunteers put forward. At the renovation site, Ye Bao wore a mask provided by the hospital and caring people to remind volunteers to change masks in time and take temperature regularly for everyone.

Cheng told the Beijing News that the Dabie Mountains Regional Medical Center itself had not yet been occupied by patients and there was no source of infection. In order to ensure the safety of volunteers, the hospital has prepared an infrared thermometer. Volunteers are required to take their temperature when entering and leaving the hospital. In addition, the hospital has set up a special room with a sterilizer, volunteers can leave their coats in the room to be disinfected or sprayed with alcohol before leaving.

While health care workers try to help volunteers avoid the risk of infection, restaurants in Huanggang are trying to get volunteers and doctors to eat better. Xiong Tao (not his real name) and his friends have been offering free food delivery services, "We had planned to open for the third day of the eighth lunar month, and we had hoarded some ingredients, but now we can't open for business, so we thought we'd make these things for free to the medical staff and volunteers, and make sure it won't be the same every day, " Xiong said.

Volunteers crouch on the floor to eat lunch boxes

Starting from January 25, Xiong Tao's caring ordering service will receive about 1,500 orders every day, with a maximum of 1,700 meals delivered a day. He started taking orders at 8 a.m. , determined the number and location of deliveries, contacted volunteers with cars to deliver meals, and did not return home until after 11 p.m. "I slept four hours a day these days, but when I got there, I felt like I hadn't done enough. "

"On January 28, when we were running out of ingredients, the owner of another restaurant sent over the ingredients he had stocked, " Xiong said. "We were supposed to be competitors. "

At noon that day, the volunteers officially finished their work and were evacuated from the Dabie Mountains Medical Center. More than 500 medical staff should also seize the time to complete the installation of isolation ward facilities, medical equipment debugging and other professional work.
